  "prompt": "What type of probability problems should be modeled as [math]Arcsine[/math] distribution?",
  "response": "The Arcsine distribution is a specialized probability distribution used in specific scenarios:\n\n1. Timing Problems:\n- First or last arrival times in certain random processes\n- Uniformly distributed initial times within an interval\n\n2. Proportion/Ratio Problems:\n- Proportion of time a random process spends in a particular state\n- Fraction of time spent in a specific region or condition\n\n3. Specific Characteristics:\n- Skewed near endpoints of intervals\n- Highest probability density near 0 and 1\n- Symmetric about 0.5\n- Particularly useful when events are concentrated near interval boundaries\n\n4. Examples:\n- Brownian motion path crossing probabilities\n- Random walk boundary crossing times\n- Proportion of time a stochastic process is above/below a threshold\n\n5. Mathematical Properties:\n- Defined on interval [0,1]\n- Probability density peaks at interval endpoints\n- Decreases toward interval center\n\nKey insight: Arcsine distribution models situations where extreme or boundary events are more likely than central events.\n\nTypical use cases involve probabilistic processes with non-uniform time/proportion distributions near interval boundaries.",
